   "source": [
    "# Widget Experiment 1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sometimes you want to interactively visualize both the Target Pixel File pixel data and the resultant lightcurve.  In this notebook we develop a concept for an experimental Jupyter widget that will allow a user to move a slider bar to see the tpf pixel image and lightcurve evolve through time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from lightkurve import KeplerTargetPixelFile\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The source **EPIC 212593538** is KSN2015k from [Rest et al. 2018](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-018-0423-2).  The source has a press release from [STScI](http://hubblesite.org/news_release/news/2018-18) and [NASA](https://www.nasa.gov/feature/jpl/kepler-beyond-planets-finding-exploding-stars)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "INFO: Found cached file ./mastDownload/K2/ktwo212593538-c06_lc/ktwo212593538-c06_lpd-targ.fits.gz with expected size 3652318. [astroquery.query]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tpf = KeplerTargetPixelFile.from_archive('212593538')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The target appears in K2's campaign 6."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,

     "data": {

     },
     "execution_count": 3,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"

   ]
  },
  {

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Setting the matplotlib plotting backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Matplotlib in Jupyter offers different outputs depending on the desired behavior.  A figure may be saved to a file, or placed into its own window (like the ipython default), or embedded directly into the notebook alongside the code and explanatory material.  This latter, popular, *inline* method can be achieved by executing the following line before figures:\n",
    "\n",
    "```ipython\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Additional, interactive functionality can be achieved with the notebook functionality:\n",
    "\n",
    "```ipython\n",
    "%matplotlib notebook\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Some common pitfalls in Jupyter widgets appear to center on the choice of backend, as evinced by [this Stack Overflow question](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44329068/jupyter-notebook-interactive-plot-with-widgets).  [This long GitHub Issue](https://github.com/jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets/issues/1179) suggests that the widget-Jupyter interaction behavior appears to have changed in different versions of Jupyter and/or ipywidgets.  After some experimentation, I found that the `%matplotlib notebook` backend seems to work:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",

     ]

       "// A function to construct a web socket function for onmessage handling.\n",

       "mpl.figure.prototype._make_on_message_function = function(fig) {\n",

       "\n",

       "                evt.data);\n",

       "            fig.waiting = false;\n",
       "            return;\n",
       "        }\n",
       "        else if (typeof evt.data === 'string' && evt.data.slice(0, 21) == \"data:image/png;base64\") {\n",
       "            fig.imageObj.src = evt.data;\n",
       "            fig.updated_canvas_event();\n",
       "            fig.waiting = false;\n",
       "            return;\n",

       "        var msg = JSON.parse(evt.data);\n",

   "source": [
    "We can assemble a photometric mask that includes all pixels except for the always-`nan` pixel."

   "source": [
    "nan_mask = np.all(np.isnan(tpf.flux), axis=0)\n",
    "empty_mask = tpf.pipeline_mask * False\n",
    "aper_mask = empty_mask\n",
    "aper_mask[1:-1, 1:-1] = True\n",
    "back_mask = ~aper_mask & ~nan_mask"
   ]

       "            fig.waiting = false;\n",
       "            return;\n",

       "            return;\n",

       "                // console.log(\"Handling '\" + msg_type + \"' message: \", msg);\n",

       "// from http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1114465/getting-mouse-location-in-canvas\n",

       "mpl.toolbar_items = [[\"Home\", \"Reset original view\", \"fa fa-home icon-home\", \"home\"], [\"Back\", \"Back to  previous view\", \"fa fa-arrow-left icon-arrow-left\", \"back\"], [\"Forward\", \"Forward to next view\", \"fa fa-arrow-right icon-arrow-right\", \"forward\"], [\"\", \"\", \"\", \"\"], [\"Pan\", \"Pan axes with left mouse, zoom with right\", \"fa fa-arrows icon-move\", \"pan\"], [\"Zoom\", \"Zoom to rectangle\", \"fa fa-square-o icon-check-empty\", \"zoom\"], [\"\", \"\", \"\", \"\"], [\"Download\", \"Download plot\", \"fa fa-floppy-o icon-save\", \"download\"]];\n",

       "mpl.default_extension = \"png\";var comm_websocket_adapter = function(comm) {\n",

       "            fig.waiting = false;\n",
       "            return;\n",

       "        // the figure and JSON message as its only arguments.\n",

       "            return;\n",

       "                // console.log(\"Handling '\" + msg_type + \"' message: \", msg);\n",

       "// from http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1114465/getting-mouse-location-in-canvas\n",
       "mpl.findpos = function(e) {\n",

       "mpl.toolbar_items = [[\"Home\", \"Reset original view\", \"fa fa-home icon-home\", \"home\"], [\"Back\", \"Back to  previous view\", \"fa fa-arrow-left icon-arrow-left\", \"back\"], [\"Forward\", \"Forward to next view\", \"fa fa-arrow-right icon-arrow-right\", \"forward\"], [\"\", \"\", \"\", \"\"], [\"Pan\", \"Pan axes with left mouse, zoom with right\", \"fa fa-arrows icon-move\", \"pan\"], [\"Zoom\", \"Zoom to rectangle\", \"fa fa-square-o icon-check-empty\", \"zoom\"], [\"\", \"\", \"\", \"\"], [\"Download\", \"Download plot\", \"fa fa-floppy-o icon-save\", \"download\"]];\n",

       "mpl.default_extension = \"png\";var comm_websocket_adapter = function(comm) {\n",

    "from ipywidgets import interact\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from bokeh.io import push_notebook, show, output_notebook\n",
    "from bokeh.plotting import figure\n",
    "from bokeh.models import Span\n",
    "from bokeh.layouts import row\n",
    "output_notebook(hide_banner=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "x = np.linspace(0, 8)\n",
    "y = np.linspace(0, 8)\n",
    "\n",
    "p = figure(title=\"widget demo: KSN2015k\", plot_height=300, plot_width=600, y_range=(80, 115), )\n",
    "r = p.line(lc.time, lc.flux, color=\"#2222aa\", line_width=3, )\n",
    "r2 = p.line([lc.time[800], lc.time[800] ],[80, 115], color=\"#aa2222\", line_width=3)\n",
    "\n",
    "s2 = figure(plot_width=300, plot_height=300, title='Difference TPF')\n",
    "s2_dat = s2.image([tpf.flux[800,:,:] - tpf.flux[643,:,:]], x=0, y=0, dw=8, dh=8)#, palette=\"Spectral11\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def update(f):\n",
    "    r2.data_source.data['x'] = [lc.time[f], lc.time[f]]\n",
    "    s2_dat.data_source.data['image'] = [tpf.flux[f,:,:] -tpf.flux[643,:,:]]\n",
    "    push_notebook()\n",
    "\n",
    "show(row(p, s2), notebook_handle=True);"
   ]

    "class KeplerTargetPixelFile(KeplerTargetPixelFileBase):\n",
    "    '''extra functionality for the KeplerTargerPixelFile'''\n",
    "    def quick_look(self, frame=0, cadenceno=None, bkg=False, aperture_mask=None,\n",
    "         show_colorbar=True, mask_color='pink', style='fast', **kwargs):\n",
    "        \"\"\"\n",
    "        Plot a target pixel file at a given frame (index) or cadence number.\n",
    "\n",
    "        Parameters\n",
    "        ----------\n",
    "        ax : matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot\n",
    "            A matplotlib axes object to plot into. If no axes is provided,\n",
    "            a new one will be generated.\n",
    "        frame : int\n",
    "            Frame number. The default is 0, i.e. the first frame.\n",
    "        cadenceno : int, optional\n",
    "            Alternatively, a cadence number can be provided.\n",
    "            This argument has priority over frame number.\n",
    "        bkg : bool\n",
    "            If True, background will be added to the pixel values.\n",
    "        aperture_mask : ndarray\n",
    "            Highlight pixels selected by aperture_mask.\n",
    "        show_colorbar : bool\n",
    "            Whether or not to show the colorbar\n",
    "        mask_color : str\n",
    "            Color to show the aperture mask\n",
    "        style : str\n",
    "            matplotlib.pyplot.style.context, default is 'fast'\n",
    "        kwargs : dict\n",
    "            Keywords arguments passed to `lightkurve.utils.plot_image`.\n",
    "\n",
    "        Returns\n",
    "        -------\n",
    "        ax : matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot\n",
    "            The matplotlib axes object.\n",
    "        \"\"\"\n",
    "        if (style == \"fast\") and (\"fast\" not in plt.style.available):\n",
    "            style = \"default\"\n",
    "        if cadenceno is not None:\n",
    "            try:\n",
    "                frame = np.argwhere(cadenceno == self.cadenceno)[0][0]\n",
    "            except IndexError:\n",
    "                raise ValueError(\"cadenceno {} is out of bounds, \"\n",
    "                                 \"must be in the range {}-{}.\".format(\n",
    "                                    cadenceno, self.cadenceno[0], self.cadenceno[-1]))\n",
    "        try:\n",
    "            if bkg and np.any(np.isfinite(self.flux_bkg[frame])):\n",
    "                pflux = self.flux[frame] + self.flux_bkg[frame]\n",
    "            else:\n",
    "                pflux = self.flux[frame]\n",
    "        except IndexError:\n",
    "            raise ValueError(\"frame {} is out of bounds, must be in the range \"\n",
    "                             \"0-{}.\".format(frame, self.shape[0]))\n",
    "        with plt.style.context(style):\n",
    "            ax = plot_image(pflux, ax=ax, title='Kepler ID: {}'.format(self.keplerid),\n",
    "                    extent=(self.column, self.column + self.shape[2], self.row,\n",
    "                    self.row + self.shape[1]), show_colorbar=show_colorbar, **kwargs)\n",
    "            ax.grid(False)\n",
    "        if aperture_mask is not None:\n",
    "            aperture_mask = self._parse_aperture_mask(aperture_mask)\n",
    "            for i in range(self.shape[1]):\n",
    "                for j in range(self.shape[2]):\n",
    "                    if aperture_mask[i, j]:\n",
    "                        ax.add_patch(patches.Rectangle((j+self.column, i+self.row),\n",
    "                                                       1, 1, color=mask_color, fill=True,\n",
    "                                                       alpha=.6))\n",
    "        return ax\n",
    "\n"
   ]
